plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig(ROOT / 'images' / '05_retention_curves.png', bbox_inches='tight')
plt.show()

Curves are pretty flat across cohorts - retention isn't getting better or worse over time. About 42% return in month 1, ~30% in month 2, ~27% in month 3. The biggest drop is between the first visit and month 1, so that's where you'd want to put your retention investment.

(Note: the Jan 2024 cohort doesn't have a month 3 datapoint yet because the data only goes through April 2024 + 90 days. Worth being explicit about.)
## 4. Time to first visit

For patients who DID convert, how long did it take? This is the kind of thing operations leadership always asks.
ttv_df = run_sql_file('03_time_to_conversion.sql')
ttv_df

# get the raw distribution for a violin plot - SQL can't really do this
# (well it can but it's ugly). Just easier to grab the row-level data.
raw = con.execute('''
    WITH journey AS (
        SELECT
            p.patient_id,
            p.primary_diagnosis,
            MIN(CASE WHEN e.event_name = '1_Account_Created' THEN e.event_date END) AS dt_acct,
            MIN(CASE WHEN e.event_name = '4_First_Visit' THEN e.event_date END) AS dt_visit
        FROM patients p
        JOIN events e ON p.patient_id = e.patient_id
        GROUP BY 1, 2
    )
    SELECT primary_diagnosis,
           DATE_DIFF('day', dt_acct, dt_visit) AS days
    FROM journey
    WHERE dt_visit IS NOT NULL
''').fetchdf()

raw.head()

# order by median descending so the violins read left-to-right by speed
order = ttv_df.sort_values('median_days_to_visit', ascending=False)['primary_diagnosis'].tolist()

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(11, 6))

sns.violinplot(
    data=raw, x='primary_diagnosis', y='days',
    order=order, inner='quartile', cut=0,
    ax=ax, palette=palette
)

ax.set_title('Days from account creation to first visit')
ax.set_xlabel('Primary diagnosis')
ax.set_ylabel('Days')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig(ROOT / 'images' / '06_time_to_conversion.png', bbox_inches='tight')
plt.show()

Median is ~9-10 days across all diagnoses, with a long right tail out to ~3 weeks for the slowest 10%. So time-to-visit isn't really what separates converting from non-converting patients - what matters is whether they get matched at all. Reinforces the section 2 finding.
## 5. Recommendations

### 1. Fix the endometriosis match gap (highest priority)

- The signal: 37% conversion vs 62-70% for everyone else. Gap is at Intake → Match.
- Most likely cause: not enough endo specialists on the platform.
- What to do:
  - Recruit more endometriosis specialists (supply-side)
  - In the meantime, build a "while you wait" engagement track for unmatched patients - educational content, peer support, symptom tracking. Anything to keep them around until a match opens up.
- Rough opportunity sizing: if endo conversion gets to the platform median (~62%), that's an additional ~180 first visits per ~750 endo signups, a ~66% lift in that segment.

### 2. Attack the month-0 to month-1 retention drop

- The signal: only ~42% of converted patients return in month 1.
- Cause: likely no automated re-engagement between visits.
- What to do: post-visit follow-up sequence — provider message at day 7, symptom check-in at day 21, scheduling nudge at day 25. A/B test against no-touch.

### 3. Better instrumentation on the match step

- We can see THAT the match step is the bottleneck but not WHY (provider availability? insurance? geography?).
- What to do: granular event tracking on the match flow specifically — match request created, providers offered, patient selected, appointment booked. Without this we're just guessing.

